t | 99.0\n560\t | 90.5\n561\t | 97.0\n562\t | 12.0\n563\t | 27.0\n564\t | 57.5\n565\t | 70.8\n566\t | 22.1\n567\t\n568\t | HS-steer\n569\t | 76.5\n570\t | 100.0\n571\t | 45.5\n572\t | 98.5\n573\t | 97.0\n574\t | 90.5\n575\t | 96.5\n576\t | 21.5\n577\t | 31.0\n578\t | 56.0\n579\t | 71.3\n580\t | 21.2\n581\t\n582\t | LLM-amplify\n583\t | 50.5\n584\t | 40.5\n585\t | 25.0\n586\t | 70.5\n587\t | 52.5\n588\t | 50.0\n589\t | 60.0\n590\t | 12.5\n591\t | 20.5\n592\t | 20.0\n593\t | 40.2\n594\t | 15.2\n595\t\n596\t | IAAN (Ours)\n597\t | 79.0\n598\t | 100.0\n599\t | 47.0\n600\t | 98.5\n601\t | 97.0\n602\t | 91.0\n603\t | 96.5\n604\t | 56.0\n605\t | 26.0\n606\t | 59.0\n607\t | 75.0\n608\t | 17.2\n609\t\n610\t | Proprietary Models\n611\t\n612\t | \n613\tGPT-4o Audio†\n614\t\n615\t | 4.5\n616\t | 1.0\n617\t | 0.0\n618\t | 7.0\n619\t | 5.0\n620\t | 8.0\n621\t | 5.0\n622\t | 0.5\n623\t | 27.0\n624\t | 28.0\n625\t | 8.6\n626\t | 81.6\n627\t\n628\t | \n629\tGemini 2.5 Flash†\n630\t\n631\t | 15.0\n632\t | 14.5\n633\t | 6.0\n634\t | 19.0\n635\t | 31.0\n636\t | 16.0\n637\t | 13.0\n638\t | 19.0\n639\t | 21.0\n640\t | 92.5\n641\t | 24.7\n642\t | 60.5\n643\t\n644\t## \n645\tV-A Main Results\n646\t\n647\tTable I reports the main VoxParadox results. Without intervention, the three open-source LALMs achieve only 7.6%7.6\\%–21.2%21.2\\% average accuracy, with average ALA reaching 64.0%64.0\\%–76.9%76.9\\%. IAAN consistently improves accuracy while reducing ALA, raising accuracy by 25.725.7, 21.421.4, and 9.79.7 points on AF3, Qwen2.5, and Kimi, respectively, while lowering ALA by 35.035.0, 28.828.8, and 21.021.0 points. With IAAN, all three models surpass the closed-source systems in Table I on both Acc and ALA, including Gemini 2.5 Flash (24.7% Acc, 60.5% ALA). This joint Acc increase and ALA decrease show that IAAN produces more acoustically grounded predictions rather than merely changing errors, and the gains hold across most attributes rather than a few.\n648\t\n649\tWe also apply IAAN to AF3-PD, a model explicitly fine-tuned to prioritize acoustic evidence [21]. IAAN still improves overall accuracy (70.5%→75.0%70.5\\%\\rightarrow 75.0\\%) and reduces ALA (22.4%→17.2%22.4\\%\\rightarrow 17.2\\%): on attributes where AF3-PD already performs well, accuracy is maintained or further improved, while on intonation, the attribute where AF3-PD still struggles, accuracy rises substantially (15.5%→56.0%15.5\\%\\rightarrow 56.0\\%). This indicates that the encoder-side signal IAAN amplifies is complementary to what such training already supplies.\n650\t\n651\t## \n652\tV-B Locus and Granularity Comparison\n653\t\n654\tWe compare IAAN with interventions at other model components to test whether the gains depend on acting inside the encoder and on selecting individual neurons rather than coarser directions (Table I).\n655\t\n656\tAfter the encoder, both audio-aware decoding (AAD), which contrasts\n657\toutput logits, and LLM-amplify, which amplifies language-model\n658\tfeed-forward neurons using the same acoustic-rank criterion as\n659\tIAAN, fail to recover the gain: AAD changes accuracy by at most a\n660\tfew points in either direction across all four models. LLM-amplify\n661\tleaves AF3, Qwen2.5, and Kimi near baseline while reducing\n662\tAF3-PD substantially (70.5%→40.2%70.5\\%\\rightarrow 40.2\\%). Neither contrasting logits nor amplifying neurons after the encoder recovers the acoustic signal that IAAN amplifies inside it.\n663\t\n664\tAt the same encoder locus as IAAN, hidden-state steering (HS-steer) adds a dense steering vector to the residual stream at the encoder layer where IAAN-selected neurons concentrate, typically near the encoder output (Sec. IV). This contrasts dense representation-level steering with sparse neuron-level amplification. HS-steer yields only modest accuracy gains on AF3 and Qwen2.5, lowers accuracy on Kimi, and barely changes AF3-PD, reaching 20.9%20.9\\%, 13.7%13.7\\%, 18.2%18.2\\%, and 71.3%71.3\\% accuracy for AF3, Qwen2.5, Kimi, and AF3-PD, respectively, compared with 38.8%38.8\\%, 29.0%29.0\\%, 30.9%30.9\\%, and 75.0%75.0\\% for IAAN. Thus, acting at the right locus is not sufficient: a dense direction mixes the few neurons carrying acoustic evidence with many irrelevant dimensions, diluting the signal isolated by IAAN.\n665\t\n666\tIAAN achieves the highest accuracy among all compared methods on every model while also lowering ALA, unlike LLM-amplify, whose lower ALA on AF3-PD (22.4%→15.2%22.4\\%\\rightarrow 15.2\\%) comes with a collapse in accuracy (70.5%→40.2%70.5\\%\\rightarrow 40.2\\%) rather than more voice-grounded answers. IAAN is the only method that consistently produces more acoustically grounded predictions across all four models.\n667\t\n668\tTABLE II: Hyperparameter sweep over neuron budget KK and gain gg. Left: listening advantage LA={=}Acc−{-}ALA (%, ↑\\uparrow) on the LISTEN development set; right: Acc (%, ↑\\uparrow) on VoxParadox. Unamplified baselines shown as development / test. Bold: best result per model per dataset; †\\dagger: configuration selected by maximizing development-set LA.\n669\t\n670\t | \n671\t | \n672\t\n673\t | LISTEN dev — LA (%)\n674\t | VoxParadox test — Acc (%)\n675\t\n676\t | Model\n677\t | \n678\t\n679\tKK\n680\t\n681\t | \n682\tgain gg\n683\t\n684\t | \n685\tgain gg\n686\t\n687\t | \n688\t | \n689\t\n690\t | \n691\t\n692\t4\n693\t\n694\t | \n695\t\n696\t8\n697\t\n698\t | \n699\t\n700\t12\n701\t\n702\t | \n703\t\n704\t16\n705\t\n706\t | \n707\t\n708\t4\n709\t\n710\t | \n711\t\n712\t8\n713\t\n714\t | \n715\t\n716\t12\n717\t\n718\t | \n719\t\n720\t16\n721\t\n722\t | \n723\t\n724\tAudio-Flamingo-3\n725\t[2pt]Baseline (unamplified):\n726\t27.4 / 13.1\n727\t\n728\t | \n729\t\n730\t50\n731\t\n732\t | \n733\t\n734\t47.4\n735\t\n736\t | \n737\t\n738\t54.2\n739\t\n740\t | \n741\t\n742\t55.3\n743\t\n744\t | \n745\t\n746\t60.0\n747\t\n748\t | \n749\t\n750\t31.9\n751\t\n752\t | \n753\t\n754\t41.5\n755\t\n756\t | \n757\t\n758\t40.8\n759\t\n760\t | \n7