\n986\t | \n987\t\n988\t1000\n989\t\n990\t | \n991\t\n992\t22.1\n993\t\n994\t | \n995\t\n996\t35.3\n997\t\n998\t | \n999\t\n1000\t32.1\n1001\t\n1002\t | \n1003\t\n1004\t27.4\n1005\t\n1006\t | \n1007\t\n1008\t7.8\n1009\t\n1010\t | \n1011\t\n1012\t29.2\n1013\t\n1014\t | \n1015\t\n1016\t29.4\n1017\t\n1018\t | \n1019\t\n1020\t29.5\n1021\t\n1022\t | \n1023\t\n1024\tKimi-Audio\n1025\t[2pt]Baseline (unamplified):\n1026\t-14.7 / 21.2\n1027\t\n1028\t | \n1029\t\n1030\t50\n1031\t\n1032\t | \n1033\t\n1034\t−-13.7\n1035\t\n1036\t | \n1037\t\n1038\t−-13.7\n1039\t\n1040\t | \n1041\t\n1042\t−-1.6\n1043\t\n1044\t | \n1045\t\n1046\t−-9.5\n1047\t\n1048\t | \n1049\t\n1050\t21.3\n1051\t\n1052\t | \n1053\t\n1054\t20.6\n1055\t\n1056\t | \n1057\t\n1058\t21.3\n1059\t\n1060\t | \n1061\t\n1062\t24.6\n1063\t\n1064\t | \n1065\t\n1066\t100\n1067\t\n1068\t | \n1069\t\n1070\t−-21.1\n1071\t\n1072\t | \n1073\t\n1074\t−-6.3\n1075\t\n1076\t | \n1077\t\n1078\t−-7.9\n1079\t\n1080\t | \n1081\t\n1082\t−-4.2\n1083\t\n1084\t | \n1085\t\n1086\t21.1\n1087\t\n1088\t | \n1089\t\n1090\t15.1\n1091\t\n1092\t | \n1093\t\n1094\t29.9\n1095\t\n1096\t | \n1097\t\n1098\t28.4\n1099\t\n1100\t | \n1101\t\n1102\t200\n1103\t\n1104\t | \n1105\t\n1106\t−-21.6\n1107\t\n1108\t | \n1109\t\n1110\t0.0\n1111\t\n1112\t | \n1113\t\n1114\t6.8\n1115\t\n1116\t | \n1117\t\n1118\t−-6.8\n1119\t\n1120\t | \n1121\t\n1122\t20.3\n1123\t\n1124\t | \n1125\t\n1126\t27.8\n1127\t\n1128\t | \n1129\t\n1130\t30.9†\n1131\t\n1132\t | \n1133\t\n1134\t29.2\n1135\t\n1136\t | \n1137\t\n1138\t1000\n1139\t\n1140\t | \n1141\t\n1142\t−-14.2\n1143\t\n1144\t | \n1145\t\n1146\t−-9.5\n1147\t\n1148\t | \n1149\t\n1150\t−-14.7\n1151\t\n1152\t | \n1153\t\n1154\t−-36.3\n1155\t\n1156\t | \n1157\t\n1158\t11.8\n1159\t\n1160\t | \n1161\t\n1162\t27.7\n1163\t\n1164\t | \n1165\t\n1166\t27.8\n1167\t\n1168\t | \n1169\t\n1170\t27.2\n1171\t\n1172\tTABLE III: Reference ablation on VoxParadox (Acc and ALA %). We compare performance under different reference signal choices, ranging from Gaussian noise and silence to the original audio mixed with noise at varying SNR levels. The unamplified baseline is included for comparison. Bold/underline: best/second-best per column.\n1173\t\n1174\t | Model\n1175\t | Audio-Flamingo-3\n1176\t | Qwen2.5-Omni\n1177\t | Kimi-Audio\n1178\t\n1179\t | Reference Type\n1180\t | \n1181\tAcc ↑\\uparrow\n1182\t\n1183\t | \n1184\tALA ↓\\downarrow\n1185\t\n1186\t | \n1187\tAcc ↑\\uparrow\n1188\t\n1189\t | \n1190\tALA ↓\\downarrow\n1191\t\n1192\t | \n1193\tAcc ↑\\uparrow\n1194\t\n1195\t | \n1196\tALA ↓\\downarrow\n1197\t\n1198\t | Baseline (unamplified)\n1199\t | 13.1\n1200\t | 75.5\n1201\t | 7.6\n1202\t | 76.9\n1203\t | 21.2\n1204\t | 64.0\n1205\t\n1206\t | Gaussian noise\n1207\t | 38.8\n1208\t | 40.5\n1209\t | 29.0\n1210\t | 48.1\n1211\t | 30.9\n1212\t | 43.0\n1213\t\n1214\t | Blank (silence)\n1215\t | 39.4\n1216\t | 38.1\n1217\t | 28.1\n1218\t | 49.2\n1219\t | 28.1\n1220\t | 42.3\n1221\t\n1222\t | \n1223\tNoisy SNR −20-20 dB\n1224\t\n1225\t | 38.3\n1226\t | 39.1\n1227\t | 29.3\n1228\t | 48.1\n1229\t | 29.7\n1230\t | 42.7\n1231\t\n1232\t | \n1233\tNoisy SNR −10-10 dB\n1234\t\n1235\t | 29.1\n1236\t | 50.1\n1237\t | 24.6\n1238\t | 49.6\n1239\t | 28.4\n1240\t | 43.4\n1241\t\n1242\t | \n1243\tNoisy SNR 0 dB\n1244\t\n1245\t | 19.5\n1246\t | 63.7\n1247\t | 14.3\n1248\t | 68.1\n1249\t | 28.5\n1250\t | 43.9\n1251\t\n1252\t | \n1253\tNoisy SNR +10+10 dB\n1254\t\n1255\t | 18.3\n1256\t | 65.9\n1257\t | 12.4\n1258\t | 72.7\n1259\t | 28.1\n1260\t | 44.7\n1261\t\n1262\t | \n1263\tNoisy SNR +20+20 dB\n1264\t\n1265\t | 21.9\n1266\t | 62.7\n1267\t | 10.8\n1268\t | 73.6\n1269\t | 30.6\n1270\t | 43.7\n1271\t\n1272\t## \n1273\tV-C Hyperparameter Sensitivity\n1274\t\n1275\tTable II reports accuracy on VoxParadox and listening advantage on the LISTEN development set across the full (K,g)(K,g) grid. Hyperparameter sensitivity is model-dependent, ranging from AF3, which remains above the unamplified baseline across all configurations on both datasets, to Kimi, which has configurations falling below baseline on both. The optimal gain ranges from g=8g{=}8 to g=16g{=}16 across models, and the optimal neuron budget from K=50K{=}50 to K=200K{=}200, suggesting that too small a gain or too large a neuron budget is unlikely to be optimal, though the specific thresholds vary by model.\n1276\t\n1277\tDespite this variation, nearly 90%90\\% of configurations across all three models outperform the unamplified baseline on VoxParadox. This shows that the method does not require precise tuning: hyperparameter choice affects how much improvement is obtained, not whether improvement occurs at all.\n1278\tThe improvement found on the development set transfers to VoxParadox, with the configurations selected on the former losing within about 3 points relative to the per-model testing performance optimum, confirming that tuning on an external held-out set is sufficient. Developing principled methods for automatically selecting (K,g)(K,g) without a held-out development set remains an avenue for future work.\n1279\t\n1280\t## \n1281\tV-D Reference Ablation\n1282\t\n1283\tIAAN contrasts each neuron’s activation on the real clip with that on a reference (Eq. 1); we ablate this\n1284\treference choice in Table III. Gaussian noise is a clip of\n1285\trandom noise constructed as described in Sec. III-B, and\n1286\tblank is a clip of silence. The noisy conditions instead add noise on\n1287\ttop of the original input clip at varying levels, with higher SNR\n1288\tretaining a larger share of the original audio.\n1289\t\n1290\tGaussian noise and blank silence give similar performance across all\n1291\tthree models (Table III). At SNR −20-20 dB, where the added noise dominates and little of the source clip remains audible, performance is also close to Gaussian noise and silence, as all three references carry little source-audio information.\n1292\t\n1293\tAs SNR increases and the reference preserves more of the source clip, accuracy drops on AF3 (38.3%38.3\\% at SNR −20-20 dB to 21.9%21.9\\% at SNR +20+20 dB) and Qwen2.5 (29.3%29.3\\% to 10.8%10.8\\%), with ALA rising accordingly. Kimi is less sensitive, remaining within 2828–31%31\\% across SNRs. Even at high SNR, where the reference is less suitable for isolating acoustic sensitivity, IAAN remains above the unamplified baselines on AF3 and Qwen2.5 (Table III), suggesting that a suboptimal reference reduces but does not eliminate the gain.\n1294\t\n1295\tThis pattern is consistent with the contrast in Eq. 1:\n1296\twhen the reference still carries some of the source clip’s acoustic\n1297\tcontent, that shared content is present in both passes and cancels out\n1298\tof the difference, leaving a noisier estimate of which neurons respond\n1299\tspecifically to the real audio.\n1300\t\n1301\t(a) Acoustic-score distribution\n1302\t\n1303\t(b) Selected neurons per encoder layer\n1304\t\n1305\tFigure 2: Acoustic-score distribution and layer localization. Statistics are averaged over all test examples. (a) Distribution of the acoustic score sis_{i} over AF3 neurons; the red dashed line marks the selection threshold. (b) Share of selected neurons in each audio encoder layer.\n1306\t\n1307\t## \n1308\tVI Analysis\n1309\t\n1310\t## \n1311\tVI-A Acoustic Score Distribution and Neuron Localization\n1312\t\n1313\tTABLE IV: VoxParadox Acc and ALA (%) for controls on neuron selection. Rows: unamplified baseline, Random, Layer-amplify, layer-restricted IAAN, and IAAN. Bold: best per column.\n1314\t\n1315\t | Model\n1316\t | Audio-Flamingo-3\n1317\t | Qwen2.5-Omni\n1318\t | Kimi-Audio\n1319\t\n1320\t | Method\n1321\t | \n1322\tAcc ↑\\uparrow\n1323\t\n1324\t | \n1325\tALA ↓\\downarrow\n1326\t\n1327\t | \n1328\tAcc ↑\\uparrow\n1329\t\n1330\t | \n1331\tALA ↓\\downarrow\n1332\t\n1333\t | \n1334\tAcc ↑\\uparrow\n1335\t\n1336\t | \n1337\tALA ↓\\downarrow\n1338\t\n1339\t | Baseline (unamplified)\n1340\t | 13.1\n1341\t | 75.5\n1342\t | 7.6\n1343\t | 76.9\n1344\t | 21.2\n1345\t | 64.0\n1346\t\n1347\t | Random\n1348\t | 13.2\n1349\t | 75.3\n1350\t | 7.8\n1351\t | 76.6\n1352\t | 24.6\n1353\t | 60.3\n1354\t\n1355\t | Layer-amplify\n1356\t | 12.4\n1357\t | 76.7\n1358\t | 7.8\n1359\t | 77.0\n1360\t | 21.5\n1361\t | 63.9\n1362\t\n1363\t | IAAN (Layer-restricted)\n1364\t | 37.2\n1365\t | 41.1\n1366\t | 29.0\n1367\t | 48.1\n1368\t | 20.7\n1369\t | 62.8\n1370\t\n1371\t | IAAN\n1372\t | 38.8\n1373\t | 40.5\n1374\t | 29.0\n1375\t | 48.1\n1376\t | 30.9\n1377\t | 43.0\n1378\t\n1379\tIAAN amplifies at most 0.12%0.12\\% of the encoder’s feed-forward neurons (K=200K{=}200 out of N=163,840N{=}163{,}840), yet raises accuracy substantially, by +9.7+9.7 to +25.7+25.7 points. Such a large effect from so few neurons leads us to examine the distribution of the acoustic score itself, to see whether responsiveness to acoustic information is broadly shared across the encoder or concentrated in a small subset of neurons. Taking AF3 as an example, Fig. 2a shows that the acoustic score is sharply concentrated near zero: the great majority of neurons respond almost identically to the real audio and to the noise reference. Only a small tail breaks away from this majority. The K=50K{=}50 selection threshold, si=0.40s_{i}{=}0.40, sits about 1313 standard deviations above the mean of this score distribution, well outside the majority rather than at an arbitrary cut along a smooth distribution.\n1380\t\n1381\tFig. 2b indicates the selected neurons are unevenly distributed across encoder layers. For AF3 and Qwen2.5, the majority of them fall in the encoder’s last layer, whereas for Kimi they are spread more widely across layers; even so, the final layer still holds a higher share of selected neurons than any other individual layer, so the tendency toward the encoder’s output holds to some degree across all three models. Why later layers exhibit this stronger acoustic-discriminative response remains an open question; further investigation could shed light on how acoustic information is organized across the encoder’s depth, which we leave to future work.\n1382\t\n1383\t## \n1384\tVI-B Selection of the Acoustic Neurons Drives the Gain\n1385\t\n1386\tTABLE V: Qualitative examples showing how IAAN changes free-text acoustic descriptions on AF3. For each attribute, the Input column gives the spoken content and two labels: the voice attribute (ground truth) and the adversarial label. The Output column shows responses from the unamplified baseline and IAAN.\n1387\t\n1388\t | \n1389\t\n1390\tAttribute\n1391\t\n1392\t | \n1393\t\n1394\tInput\n1395\t\n1396\t | \n1397\t\n1398\tMethod\n1399\t\n1400\t | \n1401\t\n1402\tOutput\n1403\t\n1404\t | \n1405\t\n1406\tGender\n1407\t\n1408\t | \n1409\t\n1410\tSpoken content: “As a female, I feel empowered to share my story.”\n1411\tVoice attribute: ✓ male\n1412\tAdversarial label: ✗ female.\n1413\t\n1414\t | \n1415\t\n1416\t \n1417\t\n1418\tBaseline\n1419\t\n1420\t(unamplified)\n1421\t\n1422\t | \n1423\t\n1424\t✗ “The speaker is a young adult female with a high-pitched, confident, and assertive voice. She sounds empowered and self-assured, with a clear and steady tone that conveys strength and determination.”\n1425\t\n1426\t | \n1427\t | \n1428\t | \n1429\t\n1430\tIAAN\n1431\t\n1432\t | \n1433\t\n1434\t✓ “The speaker is a young male with a high-pitched, angry voice, speaking in a flat, monotone manner.”\n1435\t\n1436\t | \n1437\t\n1438\tEmotion\n1439\t\n1440\t | \n1441\t\n1442\tSpoken content: “Right now, my heart is calm and steady.”\n1443\tVoice attribute: ✓ angry\n1444\tAdversarial label: ✗ neutral.\n1445\t\n1446\t | \n1447\t\n1448\t \n1449\t\n1450\tBaseline\n1451\t\n1452\t(unamplified)\n1453\t\n1454\t | \n1455\t\n1456\t✗ “The speaker in this audio is a female with a calm and steady voice.”\n1457\t\n1458\t | \n1459\t | \n1460\t | \n1461\t\n1462\tIAAN\n1463\t\n1464\t | \n1465\t\n1466\t✓ “The speaker in this audio is a young male with a high-pitched, slightly nasal voice. He sounds slightly annoyed and impatient, and his voice is quite monotone.”\n1467\t\n1468\t | \n1469\t\n1470\tSpeaker count\n1471\t\n1472\t | \n1473\t\n1474\tSpoken content: “I am alone in this discussion. Yes, absolutely. Just one person.”\n1475\tVoice attribute: ✓ two speakers\n1476\tAdversarial label: ✗ one.\n1477\t\n1478\t | \n1479\t\n1480\t \n1481\t\n1482\tBaseline\n1483\t\n1484\t(unamplified)\n1485\t\n1486\t | \n1487\t\n1488\t✗ “I hear one person speaking in this audio. The speaker is a male with a deep voice.”\n1489\t\n1490\t | \n1491\t | \n1492\t | \n1493\t\n1494\tIAAN\n1495\t\n1496\t | \n1497\t\n1498\t✓ “I hear two distinct speakers in this audio. One is a male voice speaking in a deep, resonant tone, and the other is a female voice speaking in a higher, more melodic tone.”\n1499\t\n1500\tSec. IV shows that the neurons IAAN selects are often concentrated\n1501\tin a single encoder layer. This raises the question of whether the gain depends on selecting\n1502\tthese particular neurons, or whether amplifying that layer as a whole would work just as well.\n1503\tWe test this with three controls on the encoder, each isolating one factor: random selection\n1504\t(Random), whole-layer amplification (Layer-amplify), and selection restricted to the layer\n1505\twhere most of IAAN’s selected neurons concentrate (IAAN (Layer-restricted)). Since Layer-amplify operates at a much larger scale than a small neuron subset, we re-select its gain gg\n1506\tseparately on the same LISTEN development set (Sec. IV-C).\n1507\tTable IV reports VoxParadox performance for all three controls. We focus the\n1508\tdiscussion below on accuracy; ALA follows the same trends across all three controls.\n1509\t\n1510\tRandom selection keeps the neuron budget fixed but replaces IAAN’s selected neurons with the same number of randomly chosen encoder neurons, averaged over three random seeds.\n1511\tIt offers at small\n1512\timprovement over baseline across all three models, far short of IAAN’s gains, indicating\n1513\tthat the gain comes from the acoustic-score selection itself, not merely from amplifying the\n1514\tsame number of neurons. Layer-amplify removes selection entirely, uniformly scaling every\n1515\tneuron in the layer where most of IAAN’s selected neurons concentrate, at its best gain. It\n1516\tstays at baseline, indicating that amplifying this layer without selecting within it does not\n1517\thelp either.\n1518\t\n1519\tWe then evaluate IAAN (Layer-restricted): for each model, we identify the encoder layer containing the largest share of neurons selected by full IAAN, then rerun the selection within that layer using the same neuron budget. This tests whether IAAN still works once the layer is fixed.\n1520\tFor Qwen2.5, this recovers the gain in\n1521\tfull, reaching the same accuracy as full IAAN (29.0%29.0\\%); for AF3, it recovers\n1522\tmost of the gain (37.2%37.2\\% against 38.8%38.8\\%). On Kimi, however, this restriction performs\n1523\tbelow the unamplified baseline (20.7%20.7\\% against 21.2%21.2\\%) and falls well short of full\n1524\tIAAN (30.9%30.9\\%). Unlike AF3 and Qwen2.5, Kimi’s selected neurons\n1525\tare not as strongly concentrated in a single layer, and a considerable portion lie outside\n1526\twhichever layer the restriction targets. Restricting the search to a single layer therefore\n1527\texcludes many of the neurons IAAN would otherwise select. This indicates that searching\n1528\tacross the full encoder, as IAAN does, is necessary to reach these neurons on models like\n1529\tKimi, where their distribution across layers is less concentrated.\n1530\t\n1531\tCombining these controls with the locus and granularity comparison (Sec. V-B), we confirm that both the encoder as the intervention site and the selectivity of the neuron set within it are necessary for IAAN’s gain. These results further suggest that the acoustic score provides a reliable signal for identifying which neurons matter across the full encoder, even without task labels or a calibration set.\n1532\t\n1533\t## \n1534\tVI-C Qualitative Results\n1535\t\n1536\tBeyond multiple-choice evaluation, we examine free-text descriptions to test whether IAAN changes how the model describes acoustic properties, rather than only which option it selects (Table V). Across the three examples, the baseline often misdescribes key cues such as gender, emotion, and speaker count, while IAAN produces descriptions more consistent with the actual voice. These shifts mirror the quantitative results: amplifying acoustic neurons helps the model ground its descriptions in how the audio sounds.\n1537\t\n1538\t## \n1539\tVII Conclusion\n1540\t\n1541\tWe present IAAN, a training-free and label-free method that improves acoustic understanding in large audio-language models by intervening inside the audio encoder. IAAN scores each neuron by how much more it responds to the real waveform than to a noise reference lacking the real audio’s acoustic information, then amplifies a small set of the highest-scoring neurons at inference. Across three open-source LALMs, IAAN modifies at most 0.12% of the encoder’s neurons, yet improves average accuracy by 9.7 to 25.7 points, with gains broad across attributes rather than concentrated in a few. Controlled experiments further confirm that both the encoder locus and the selectivity of the neuron set are essential to this gain. These findings establish the audio encoder’s individual neurons as an effective and largely untapped site for inference-time intervention, suggesting that deeper exploration of the encoder’s internal structure may yield further gains in acoustic understanding.\n1542\t\n1543\t## AI-Generated Content Disclosure\n1544\t\n1545\tAI tools were used only for language editing; the authors reviewed all content and take full responsibility.\n1546\t\n1547\t## Acknowledgment\n1548\t\n1549\tThis work was supported by the Ministry of Education (MOE) of Taiwan under the project Taiwan Centers of Excellence in Artificial Intelligence,